  "runtimeMin": 99,
  "format": "The day after David Lynch's death, Sean Fennessey, Amanda Dobbins, and Chris Ryan open with his films and what made them impossible to imitate, then predict the 2025 Oscar nominations across the top eight categories. They close with a full review of 'Den of Thieves 2: Pantera,' which Ryan watched in a packed theater with no subtitles.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Remembering David Lynch",
      "note": "1946–2025",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Twin Peaks: Fire Walk with Me",
          "year": 1992,
          "note": "The achievement Sean rates highest: Lynch rejecting and re-examining his own hit, refusing to let Laura Palmer be only a dead body."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mulholland Drive",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "Sean's first Lynch and his favorite. An Oscar-conversation movie that let a 17-year-old into old-Hollywood noir at the same time it upended it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Eraserhead",
          "year": 1977,
          "note": "'This is about having a baby': the fugue state of new parenthood, gnarled mutant creatures and sounds from the universe included."
        },
        {
          "title": "Inland Empire",
          "year": 2006,
          "note": "'Impossibly hard to watch and ugly and annoying,' and, they argue, the closest thing that exists to a movie about the LA fires."
        },
        {
          "title": "Lost Highway",
          "year": 1997,
          "note": "Slammed on release; the subject of Sean's 2022 Lynch episode with Adam Nayman. The not-working is the point."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dune",
          "year": 1984,
          "note": "The job he took instead of Return of the Jedi. Never quite hangs together, though the novel's oddity may suit him better than Villeneuve."
        }
      ]
    },
